<h2>Here Are Some Additional Features You May Want To Consider When Shopping For A Cat Bed:</h2>
<h3>Materials</h3>
<p>The material from which your cats bed is made should be as natural as possible. The last thing you want is for your cat to spend hours in close contact with a material that triggers a negative reaction. Unnatural fibers are more likely to have gone through a chemical cleaning process which has the potential to affect your cat one way or another.</p>
<p><strong>Materials also affect the durability of your cat bed and how easy it is to clean.</strong></p>
<p>When shopping for a cat bed, check for a removable cover. In many cases, these covers are water-resistant and machine-washable which adds a certain degree of convenience.</p>
<p>Even if a cat bed says its machine washable, however, you should still follow the instructions carefully to avoid having the bed turn out crumpled or grossly misshapen after washing. Most cat beds do best when left to air dry, though some can be put in the dryer on the lowest heat setting.</p>
<h3>Design</h3>
<p>Functionality is one of the most important things to consider when shopping for a cat bed. Is it warm enough for the colder winter months? How about summer? Does it keep your cat cool?</p>
<p>Asking questions like these can help you decide what kind of design is best for your cat.</p>
<p>Two of the most popular cat bed designs are the sleeping mat and the nest-style bed (also known as a cuddler). A sleeping mat is a fairly basic design that provides a padded surface for your cat to stretch out on. A nest bed, on the other hand, is often rounded with raised bolsters designed for cats who like to curl up when they sleep.</p>
<p>A sleeping mat may be a better option if your cat likes to stretch out or if overheating is a problem. Nest-style cat beds, on the other hand, help retain body heat for warmth.</p>
<h3>Raised</h3>
<p>As your cat ages, it may become more difficult for him to get up from lying down  especially from the floor. A raised cat bed may be easier for your aging cat to get in and out of.</p>
<p>Raised cat beds can also provide a higher degree of support than traditional sleeping mats.</p>
<p>If your cat has arthritis or other bone and joint issues, support is very important. Make sure the bed you choose isnt just overstuffed with padding  if it sinks under your cats weight it may be more difficult to get out of than if the base is made from a responsive material like memory foam.</p>
<h3>Covered</h3>
<p>Some cats choose where to sleep based on where they feel most secure. For some cats, its an elevated area where they can see around them on all sides. For others, its a covered cat bed.</p>
<p>In addition to providing a sense of security for your cat, a covered cat bed can also help keep your cat warm. Depending on the materials from which it is made, covered cat beds can retain body heat to create a self-warming effect.</p>
<h3>Size</h3>
<p>When shopping for cat beds its important to consider not only the size of the bed itself, but the size of any additional features. For example, think about the size of the opening for a covered cat bed or the size of the bolsters on a supportive nest-style cat bed.</p>
<p>As a general rule, your cats bed should be large enough for your cat to lie down and turn around in. To get an idea what size cat bed you need, measure your cat from head to the base of its tail. You may want to add a few inches to that measurement to give your cat some leeway.</p>
<h3>Cost</h3>
<p>Cat beds can be pretty expensive, so think about your budget before you start shopping. You may also want to ask yourself some questions about how many cat beds you need and where you plan to put them. If you have more than one cat, you may want to provide multiple beds.</p>
<p>The average cat bed ranges from $20-$50 while heated options are around $50- $100. Cat furniture that incorporates sleeping areas tend to be the most expensive.</p>
<h2>Consider Your Cats Sleeping Habits</h2>
<p>In addition to thinking about features like materials, durability, and design, you should think about your cats sleeping habits to guide you toward the perfect cat bed.</p>
<p>Think about where your cat tends to sleep. Does he choose an elevated area where he feels untouchable, or does he curl up in the middle of the living room floor? Does your cat prefer to stretch out while sleeping or does he curl up into a tiny ball?</p>
<p>Answering these questions will help you narrow down the options once you start shopping for a cat bed to get to the most appropriate choice for your cat.</p>
<h3>Relevant Content</h3>
<ul>
